# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alpinejs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Everything in Alpine starts with the `x-data` directive.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] `x-data` defines a chunk of HTML as an Alpine component and provides the reactive data for that component to reference.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Don't worry about the other directives in this example (`@click` and `x-show`), we'll get to those in a bit.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Properties defined in an `x-data` directive are available to all element children.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Even ones inside other, nested `x-data` components.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Because `x-data` is evaluated as a normal JavaScript object, in addition to state, you can store methods and even getters.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] For example, let's extract the "Toggle Content" behavior into a method on `x-data`.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Notice the added `toggle() { this.open = ! this.open }` method on `x-data`.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] This method can now be called from anywhere inside the component.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] You'll also notice the usage of `this.` to access state on the object itself.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] This is because Alpine evaluates this data object like any standard JavaScript object with a `this` context.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] If you prefer, you can leave the calling parenthesis off of the `toggle` method completely.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] JavaScript getters are handy when the sole purpose of a method is to return data based on other state.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Think of them like "computed properties" (although, they are not cached like Vue's computed properties).
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Let's refactor our component to use a getter called `isOpen` instead of accessing `open` directly.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Notice the "Content" now depends on the `isOpen` getter instead of the `open` property directly.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] In this case there is no tangible benefit.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] But in some cases, getters are helpful for providing a more expressive syntax in your components.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] Occasionally, you want to create an Alpine component, but you don't need any data.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] In these cases, you can always pass in an empty object.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] However, if you wish, you can also eliminate the attribute value entirely if it looks better to you.
[src:alpinejs/directives-data] If you find yourself duplicating the contents of `x-data`, or you find the inline syntax verbose, you can extract the `x-data` object out to a dedicated component using `Alpine.data`.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:alpinejs/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] State (JavaScript data that Alpine watches for changes) is at the core of everything you do in Alpine.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] You can provide local data to a chunk of HTML, or make it globally available for use anywhere on a page using `x-data` or `Alpine.store()` respectively.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] Alpine allows you to declare an HTML block's state in a single `x-data` attribute without ever leaving your markup.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] Now any other Alpine syntax on or within this element will be able to access `open`.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] And like you'd guess, when `open` changes for any reason, everything that depends on it will react automatically.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] For example, if you have two elements with Alpine data attached (one inside the other), you can access the parent's data from inside the child element.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] Like you may have guessed, if the child has a data property matching the name of a parent's property, the child property will take precedence.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] Although this may seem obvious to some, it's worth mentioning that Alpine data can be used within the same element.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] Sometimes you may want to use Alpine functionality, but don't need any reactive data.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] In these cases, you can opt out of passing an expression to `x-data` entirely.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] When using Alpine, you may find the need to re-use a chunk of data and/or its corresponding template.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] If you are using a backend framework like Rails or Laravel, Alpine first recommends that you extract the entire block of HTML into a template partial or include.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] If for some reason that isn't ideal for you or you're not in a back-end templating environment, Alpine allows you to globally register and re-use the data portion of a component using `Alpine.data(...)`.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] If you wish to make some data available to every component on the page, you can do so using Alpine's "global store" feature.
[src:alpinejs/essentials-state] You can register a store using `Alpine.store(...)`, and reference one with the magic `$store()` method.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] A **JavaScript library** is a library of pre-written JavaScript code that allows for easier development of JavaScript-based applications, especially for AJAX and other web-centric technologies.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] They can be included in a website by embedding it directly in the HTML via a script tag.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] With the expanded demands for JavaScript, an easier means for programmers to develop such dynamic interfaces was needed.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Thus, JavaScript libraries and JavaScript widget libraries were developed, allowing for developers to concentrate more upon more distinctive applications of Ajax.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] This has led to other companies and groups, such as Microsoft and Yahoo! developing their own JavaScript-based user interface libraries, which find their way into the web applications developed by these companies.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries allow for easier integration of JavaScript with other web development technologies, such as CSS, PHP, Ruby, and Java, while others provide utilities, often in the form of JavaScript functions, to make repetitive and complex tasks less taxing.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Many libraries include code to detect differences between runtime environments and remove the need for applications to allow for such inconsistencies.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Almost all JavaScript libraries are released under either a permissive or copyleft license to ensure license-free distribution, usage, and modification.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries, such as Angular, are classified as frameworks since they exhibit full-stack capabilities and properties not found in general JavaScript libraries.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] All npm packages are JavaScript libraries, but not all libraries are packages.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] Npm serves as a package manager for packages used in Node.js runtimes.
[src:alpinejs/javascript-library] However, some npm packages offer CDN support for use of the library in both Node.js runtimes as well as the browser.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:alpinejs/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Open your file in a web browser, if you see `I ❤️ Alpine`, you're ready to rumble!
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now that you're all set up to play around, let's look at three practical examples as a foundation for teaching you the basics of Alpine.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] By the end of this exercise, you should be more than equipped to start building stuff on your own.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Let's start with a simple "counter" component to demonstrate the basics of state and event listening in Alpine, two core features.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now, you can see with 3 bits of Alpine sprinkled into this HTML, we've created an interactive "counter" component.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Everything in Alpine starts with an `x-data` directive.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Inside of `x-data`, in plain JavaScript, you declare an object of data that Alpine will track.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Every property inside this object will be made available to other directives inside this HTML element.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] In addition, when one of these properties changes, everything that relies on it will change as well.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-on` is a directive you can use to listen for any event on an element.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] We're listening for a `click` event in this case, so ours looks like `x-on:click`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] You can listen for other events as you'd imagine.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] For example, listening for a `mouseenter` event would look like this: `x-on:mouseenter`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] When a `click` event happens, Alpine will call the associated JavaScript expression, `count++` in our case.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] As you can see, we have direct access to data declared in the `x-data` expression.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-text` is an Alpine directive you can use to set the text content of an element to the result of a JavaScript expression.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] In this case, we're telling Alpine to always make sure that the contents of this `span` tag reflect the value of the `count` property.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] In case it's not clear, `x-text`, like most directives accepts a plain JavaScript expression as an argument.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] So for example, you could instead set its contents to: `x-text="count * 2"` and the text content of the `span` will now always be 2 times the value of `count`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now that we've seen some basic functionality, let's keep going and look at an important directive in Alpine: `x-show`, by building a contrived "dropdown" component.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] If you load this component, you should see that the "Contents..." are hidden by default.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] You can toggle showing them on the page by clicking the "Toggle" button.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The `x-data` and `x-on` directives should be familiar to you from the previous example, so we'll skip those explanations.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-show` is an extremely powerful directive in Alpine that can be used to show and hide a block of HTML on a page based on the result of a JavaScript expression, in our case: `open`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] You'll notice something new in this example: `.outside`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Many directives in Alpine accept "modifiers" that are chained onto the end of the directive and are separated by periods.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] In this case, `.outside` tells Alpine to instead of listening for a click INSIDE the `<div>`, to listen for the click only if it happens OUTSIDE the `<div>`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] This is a convenience helper built into Alpine because this is a common need and implementing it by hand is annoying and complex.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Let's now build a more complex component and introduce a handful of other directives and patterns.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] By default, all of the "items" (foo, bar, and baz) will be shown on the page, but you can filter them by typing into the text input.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] As you type, the list of items will change to reflect what you're searching for.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now there's quite a bit happening here, so let's go through this snippet piece by piece.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The first thing I'd like to point out is that `x-data` now has a lot more going on in it than before.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] To make it easier to write and read, we've split it up into multiple lines in our HTML.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] This is completely optional and we'll talk more in a bit about how to avoid this problem altogether, but for now, we'll keep all of this JavaScript directly in the HTML.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] You'll notice a new directive we haven't seen yet: `x-model`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-model` is used to "bind" the value of an input element with a data property: "search" from `x-data="{ search: '', ... }"` in our case.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] This means that anytime the value of the input changes, the value of "search" will change to reflect that.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-model` is capable of much more than this simple example.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The next bit I'd like to draw your attention to is the `items` and `filteredItems` properties from the `x-data` directive.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The `items` property should be self-explanatory.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Here we are setting the value of `items` to a JavaScript array of 3 different items (foo, bar, and baz).
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The interesting part of this snippet is the `filteredItems` property.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Denoted by the `get` prefix for this property, `filteredItems` is a "getter" property in this object.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] This means we can access `filteredItems` as if it was a normal property in our data object, but when we do, JavaScript will evaluate the provided function under the hood and return the result.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] It's completely acceptable to forgo the `get` and just make this a method that you can call from the template, but some prefer the nicer syntax of the getter.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] We are first getting the array of items (foo, bar, and baz) and filtering them using the provided callback: `i => i.startsWith(this.search)`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] By passing in this callback to `filter`, we are telling JavaScript to only return the items that start with the string: `this.search`, which like we saw with `x-model` will always reflect the value of the input.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] You may notice that up until now, we haven't had to use `this.` to reference properties.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] However, because we are working directly inside the `x-data` object, we must reference any properties using `this.[property]` instead of simply `[property]`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Because Alpine is a "reactive" framework.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Any time the value of `this.search` changes, parts of the template that use `filteredItems` will automatically be updated.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now that we understand the data part of our component, let's understand what's happening in the template that allows us to loop through `filteredItems` on the page.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The first thing to notice here is the `x-for` directive.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] `x-for` expressions take the following form: `[item] in [items]` where [items] is any array of data, and [item] is the name of the variable that will be assigned to an iteration inside the loop.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Also notice that `x-for` is declared on a `<template>` element and not directly on the `<li>`.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] It allows Alpine to leverage the existing behavior of `<template>` tags in the browser to its advantage.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] Now any element inside the `<template>` tag will be repeated for every item inside `filteredItems` and all expressions evaluated inside the loop will have direct access to the iteration variable (`item` in this case).
[src:alpinejs/start-here] That's a great start, however, there are many more directives to sink your teeth into.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] The best way to absorb Alpine is to read through this documentation.
[src:alpinejs/start-here] No need to comb over every word, but if you at least glance through every page you will be MUCH more effective when using Alpine.
